snippet.textDisplay:
I never made it up to the Cape whilst I was in Australia but I seen that exact thing in a lot of different places. Once on Fraser Island in Central Station Camp Site which as you'll know has a refuse point we ran after a 2 car group (I'll refrain from naming the nationality) and forced them into taking their rubbish they'd left strewn all across their spot, apparently beer cans become useless when you empty them... They took it with them all the couple of hundred yards to the refuse point but only after quite a heated argument.

Unfortunately we have the same here in Scotland, we are lucky to have a right to roam act allowing us access through lands to wild camp, not so much 4wd but certainly hiking and being in the outdoors but that's all at risk at the moment with increasing tourism seeing people just discard what they want where they want and making trails or camp spots like what you just cleaned up.

Good effort cleaning up after the dogs.

snippet.textDisplay:
Have had the same out at Morwell River in Gippsland near Morwell river falls, many camp spots and yeah they leave the rubbish, WHY they don't take it with them ?? No common sense.
Once discovered a whole trailer load dumped directly into the river, they had backed a 4WD tray back down and emptied it. Cleaned up and dragged out what we could, called the local EPA they came and cleaned up the remainder. Had the name address and phone number among the rubbish to id the people, but they were never prosecuted. The authorities need to dish out much harder penalties and legally pursue these people, we take vehicles and boats etc.. with illegal fishing and fire wood collection why not do the same for those who dump and litter.

snippet.textDisplay:
A few years back I took my 60 year old Mum out to the Macquarie Marshes in NSW. When we jumped out at a spot in the middle of the marshes there was crap absolutely f*g everywhere. She started picking up the rubbish and bagging it. I made a comment about it and she replied "Well, who else is bloody gonna clean it up?". After that remark, me, her, ol man and a mate spent about half an hour bagging up rubbish around the marshes and took it back into town.
That attitude has really stuck with me since. We always see things as "oh that's the government's responsibility" or "that's not my problem". Sometimes you just gotta take the responsibility onto yourself.

Later on the same trip we pulled into the Paroo river at Wanaaring. On the way down to the river, passed a bunch of 4wd utes heading out, all new vehicles, kitted for touring, clean looking folks all maybe in their 40's, not yobs, they all waved as we passed them in. Got down to the river and it was f*d. Freshly broken beer bottles everywhere, bags of rubbish floating in the billabong that appeared to have just been thrown in that morning. There was a lot of older rubbish as well but it was pretty clear those neat and tidy folks with friendly faces had been absolute pigs while they were camped there. I ended up cutting my hand on broken glass while having a swim in the river.

snippet.textDisplay:
You guys are absolute champions! Love your work, and love that you guys covered this important issue in a video. Subscribed.

Back when I was in the US I used to lead backcountry camping trips with groups of teenagers, and one of rules we had was to always leave our campsites cleaner than we found them. That applied whether we were free camping 3 days out in the backcountry or at a run of the mill car camping site. Either way after we left you would never know that 15 people had just camped there.

One thing that really helped was everyone had their own garden trowel. Very handy for digging little pits to poop in. Nobody likes stepping on a landline! (or seeing them later!)
